{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13938"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.63,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76083"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1209"},{"type":"tags","id":"1210"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44184"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her parents after being bitten by a snake while playing in the backyard 30 minutes ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. A pressure immobilisation bandage has been applied to the left leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Two small puncture marks are visible on her left ankle when the bandage is briefly inspected. The snake was described as brown in colour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common clinical manifestation of this type of envenomation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paralysis","Cardiac arrhythmias","Coagulation abnormalities","Acute kidney injury","Muscle breakdown"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the geographic location and clinical presentation, this case is suggestive of a brown snake (\u003Cem\u003EPseudonaja\u003C/em\u003E) bite, which are among the most venomous snakes in Australia. Their bites can be life-threatening if not treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulation abnormalities\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common and clinically significant effect of brown snake envenomation. Brown snake venom contains potent procoagulants that cause severe disruption of the clotting cascade, leading to a consumptive coagulopathy. This results in prolonged clotting times, decreased fibrinogen levels, and increased risk of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac arrhythmias\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in severe envenomations but are not the primary or most common effect. While brown snake venom does have cardiotoxic components, these effects are generally less prominent than the coagulopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute kidney injury\u003C/strong\u003E can be a complication of severe envenomation, particularly if there is significant myolysis or prolonged hypotension. However, it is not the most common primary effect of brown snake venom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalysis\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with other Australian elapid snakes, such as tiger snakes or death adders. Brown snake venom contains some neurotoxins, but neurotoxicity is not typically a prominent feature of their envenomation syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E (rhabdomyolysis) can occur in severe cases but is not the primary effect. It is more commonly associated with other Australian snakes, such as tiger snakes or black snakes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that snake venom detection kits are no longer recommended for the treatment of snakebite in Australia. Instead, the clinical toxin syndrome and geographic location should guide antivenom selection. Management priorities include maintaining pressure immobilisation, monitoring for signs of systemic envenomation, and administering antivenom if indicated based on clinical features. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brown snake envenomation primarily causes coagulopathy, which is the most common and clinically significant effect.","Clinical toxin syndrome and geographic location, rather than venom detection kits, should guide antivenom selection in Australian snake bites.","First aid with pressure immobilisation bandaging and patient immobilisation is critical in snake bite management."],"references":["White J. Snakebites worldwide: Management. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024 [cited 2024 Jul 15]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/snakebites-worldwide-management?search=brown%20snake\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Allen GE, Brown SG, Buckley NA, O\u0027Leary MA, Page CB, Currie BJ, White J, Isbister GK; ASP Investigators. Clinical effects and antivenom dosing in brown snake (Pseudonaja spp.) envenoming--Australian snakebite project (ASP-14). PLoS One. 2012;7(12):e53188. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3532501/","https://www.rcpa.edu.au/Manuals/RCPA-Manual/Clinical-Presentations-and-Diagnoses/S/Snake-bite-envenomation"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76083"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76083"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T22:23:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T22:24:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gradua